<div id="review_2641362573" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2641362573" />
    <a title="Martha☀" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4834343-martha"><img alt="Martha☀" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1297211801p2/4834343.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2641362573?book_show_action=true">Aug 11, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Martha☀" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Martha☀" href="/user/show/4834343-martha">Martha☀</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4834343-martha?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4834343-martha?shelf=own">own</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2641362573" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2301471471777651843">From within a prison cell, Frederick Montgomery writes his own account of the murder he committed. Told in a somewhat backwards chronology, we learn of the murder early on, although it takes half the book to reach that scene. But this is not a mystery; this is a character study - and what a study it is!<br/>If you let yourself be pulled into Freddie&apos;s reality, you are in for a wild ride. On the outside, Freddie is a pathetic, repulsive murderer who is completely in denial of who he is and how he pres</span>
  <span id="freeText2301471471777651843" style="display:none">From within a prison cell, Frederick Montgomery writes his own account of the murder he committed. Told in a somewhat backwards chronology, we learn of the murder early on, although it takes half the book to reach that scene. But this is not a mystery; this is a character study - and what a study it is!<br />If you let yourself be pulled into Freddie's reality, you are in for a wild ride. On the outside, Freddie is a pathetic, repulsive murderer who is completely in denial of who he is and how he presents himself to the world. But that is not Banville's point. In this novel, we are pulled inside Freddie's persona where we witness the madness within. His thoughts are shattered, he is unable to maintain a complete thought and his stream of consciousness meanders, eddies and then goes off in random directions for the entire rendition of his actions leading up to and immediately following the murder. He justifies it all and is able to look at it with a complete lack of emotion. <br />I especially loved the part where, upon stealing a portrait of a woman, Freddie goes off on a bizarre tangent where he imagines the minute details of this painted woman's life. <br />So well-written and such a gruesome delight to read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2301471471777651843" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


